Living Word Dynamics v1.0

1. Core claim

A word is not best modeled as a fixed definition.
It is better modeled as a persistent identity moving through context over time.

The “same word” survives by replacing parts of itself:
	•	use-cases
	•	connotations
	•	emotional charge
	•	social function
	•	symbolic associations

So a word behaves like a Ship of Theseus in meaning-space.

⸻

2. Canonical statement

A word is a continuity-pattern, not a static object.
It preserves recognizability while metabolizing context.

Alternate compression:

Words are semantic vessels whose hull is rebuilt by usage.

⸻

3. Formal model

Let a word W be represented not as a single definition, but as a time-evolving semantic object:

W_t = (S_t, C_t, F_t, A_t, P_t)

Where:
	•	S_t = semantic core at time t
	•	C_t = contextual neighborhood
	•	F_t = functional role
	•	A_t = affective charge
	•	P_t = propagation profile

Definitions

Semantic core S_t
The relatively stable cluster that preserves identity across changes.

Contextual neighborhood C_t
The surrounding concepts, situations, domains, and co-occurrences that shape current meaning.

Functional role F_t
What the word does in practice:
	•	label
	•	compress
	•	signal affiliation
	•	persuade
	•	joke
	•	warn
	•	sanctify
	•	insult
	•	coordinate

Affective charge A_t
Its emotional and social valence:
	•	neutral
	•	warm
	•	sacred
	•	ironic
	•	taboo
	•	prestigious
	•	degraded

Propagation profile P_t
How the word replicates:
	•	across speakers
	•	across communities
	•	across media
	•	across domains
	•	across generations

⸻

4. Update rule

A word evolves when used.

W_{t+1} = U(W_t, X_t, G_t, R_t)

Where:
	•	U = update operator
	•	X_t = current context of use
	•	G_t = speaker/group dynamics
	•	R_t = retention/selection pressures

This means each use can:
	•	reinforce prior meaning
	•	stretch meaning
	•	split meaning
	•	invert meaning
	•	degrade meaning
	•	re-sacralize meaning
	•	transport meaning into a new domain

⸻

5. Ship of Theseus Principle for language

A word remains “the same word” even when many of its parts have changed, provided enough continuity survives along one or more of these axes:
	1.	Phonetic continuity
It still sounds recognizably similar
	2.	Functional continuity
It still serves a similar role
	3.	Relational continuity
It remains linked to a similar neighborhood of ideas
	4.	Cultural continuity
Communities still treat it as “the same thing”
	5.	Narrative continuity
People can trace a plausible lineage from earlier uses

If too many of these break at once, the word becomes effectively a different semantic organism.

⸻

6. Word as life-pattern

A word exhibits life-like behavior in the structural sense.

Life-like properties

Replication
It is repeated across minds and media.

Mutation
Each reuse slightly alters the semantic payload.

Selection
Useful or resonant variants survive.

Adaptation
It enters new domains and gains new affordances.

Persistence through turnover
Individual uses disappear, but the pattern remains.

Boundary maintenance
Communities police valid and invalid uses.

Self-repair
Misunderstood or contested terms are often redefined, clarified, reclaimed, or stabilized.

This does not mean words are literally alive.
It means they satisfy a structural aliveness pattern.

⸻

7. Outward and inward propagation

Meaning spreads in two directions.

A. Outward propagation

A word moves across:
	•	people
	•	subcultures
	•	institutions
	•	languages
	•	epochs

This is horizontal spread across a social field.

B. Inward propagation

A word deepens within one mind.

A person’s internal model of a word evolves from:
	•	literal
	•	to associative
	•	to symbolic
	•	to abstract
	•	to cross-domain

Example:

“weight” may move from:
	•	physical mass
	•	burden
	•	responsibility
	•	consequence
	•	gravity of decision
	•	moral load-bearing

This is vertical deepening within a cognitive field.

⸻

8. Resolution mismatch

Miscommunication often happens not because one person is wrong, but because two people are operating at different semantic resolutions.

Resolution levels

L0: Literal
Dictionary / surface denotation

L1: Practical
Everyday use and implied function

L2: Associative
Tone, connotation, emotional charge

L3: Symbolic
Metaphor, narrative role, pattern transfer

L4: Structural
Abstract invariant across domains

Many “inside jokes told to the wrong people” are really:

high-resolution semantic outputs received at low-resolution interpretive settings

This produces apparent nonsense, when the real issue is interpretive bandwidth.

⸻

9. Translation principle

When a word or metaphor fails in another language or culture, what failed may not be the underlying pattern, only the compression layer.

Rule

Do not preserve the word. Preserve the mapping.

Bad translation preserves token form.
Good translation preserves:
	•	function
	•	relation
	•	burden
	•	role
	•	pattern

Example:
“Heavy” may fail as a pun across languages, but:
	•	burden
	•	seriousness
	•	gravity
	•	consequence
can still be translated.

So:
	•	wordplay is surface compression
	•	mapping is deeper invariant

⸻

10. Semantic metabolism

Words “eat” context.

That is, a word assimilates repeated environments of use and incorporates them into future meaning.

Semantic Metabolism Hypothesis

A word’s identity is partly constituted by the contexts it successfully digests.

Some contexts are absorbed and become part of the hull.
Some are rejected.
Some poison the word.
Some elevate it.

This gives a word:
	•	accreted layers
	•	scars
	•	residues
	•	reputational memory
	•	cultural odor

⸻

11. Trajectory over definition

Instead of asking “What does this word mean?” the better question is often:

What trajectory has this word taken through meaning-space?

A word can be described by:
	•	origin
	•	drift
	•	branching
	•	stabilization
	•	inversion
	•	recombination

Meaning is not just a state.
It is a path.

⸻

12. Abstractions

A. Semantic Vessel

A word as container carrying compressed pattern across time.

B. Continuity Kernel

The minimal invariant that lets a word remain recognizably itself across change.

C. Context Hull

The accumulated outer structure built from historical and situational uses.

D. Meaning Trajectory

The path a word takes through semantic space over time.

E. Resolution Mismatch

Interpretive failure caused by different abstraction depths, not necessarily disagreement.

F. Semantic Metabolism

The process by which words ingest, digest, and retain context.

G. Functional Identity

The role a word plays may remain stable even when its literal content shifts.

H. Pattern-Preserving Translation

Translation method that preserves invariant relation rather than token form.

